00:11:43.010 --> 00:11:44.450 align:middle line:90%
But what about the heart?

00:11:44.450 --> 00:11:47.670 align:middle line:84%
Does the heart have the capacity
to store thoughts, memories,

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:49.070 align:middle line:90%
and emotions too?

00:11:49.070 --> 00:11:52.310 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a look as Gregg
Braden from "Missing Links"

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:55.100 align:middle line:84%
tells us about
memory and the heart.

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:58.190 align:middle line:10%
>>GREGG BRADEN: This is a story
that happened in a small town

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:00.040 align:middle line:10%
in the Midwest.

00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:03.880 align:middle line:10%
It was a story of an
eight-year-old girl

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:07.790 align:middle line:10%
who received the heart of
another little girl who

00:12:07.790 --> 00:12:11.370 align:middle line:10%
was only two years older,
a 10-year-old girl.

00:12:11.370 --> 00:12:14.820 align:middle line:84%
And the heart transplant
was successful.

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:16.290 align:middle line:10%
And typically this
is what happens.

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:20.700 align:middle line:10%
The doctors will try to match
the heart from the donor

00:12:20.700 --> 00:12:23.280 align:middle line:10%
to the recipient
within a range of ages

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:27.720 align:middle line:10%
so that a very young person
isn't getting the older

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:29.940 align:middle line:10%
heart of a very older person.

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:31.990 align:middle line:10%
So the young girl, she
received the heart.

00:12:31.990 --> 00:12:34.140 align:middle line:10%
The transplant was successful.

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.810 align:middle line:10%
But something happened
almost immediately.

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:41.430 align:middle line:10%
She began having a dream,
a reoccurring dream.

00:12:41.430 --> 00:12:42.390 align:middle line:10%
And it was a bad dream.

00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:44.550 align:middle line:10%
So we will call it a nightmare.

00:12:44.550 --> 00:12:46.560 align:middle line:10%
And she began having
this nightmare

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:47.790 align:middle line:10%
over and over and over again.

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:49.030 align:middle line:10%
It wasn't every single night.

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:50.410 align:middle line:10%
But it was multiple
times a week.

00:12:50.410 --> 00:12:53.850 align:middle line:10%
It was common enough that
her doctor recognized

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:55.790 align:middle line:10%
that something
else was going on.

00:12:55.790 --> 00:12:59.350 align:middle line:10%
And it was something that was
out of his realm of expertise.

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:01.470 align:middle line:10%
So the doctor said,
I've done my job.

00:13:01.470 --> 00:13:02.970 align:middle line:10%
I've given you a new heart.

00:13:02.970 --> 00:13:04.200 align:middle line:10%
It is successful.

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:05.870 align:middle line:10%
Now, you can go live your life.

00:13:05.870 --> 00:13:07.620 align:middle line:10%
And I think you need
to speak with someone

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:10.480 align:middle line:10%
else about the dreams
that you're experiencing.

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:13.590 align:middle line:10%
So the doctor set her
up with a psychiatrist.

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:16.500 align:middle line:10%
And the psychiatrist
recognized immediately, this

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:18.090 align:middle line:10%
wasn't a typical dream.

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:21.330 align:middle line:10%
It had the characteristics
of a memory.

00:13:21.330 --> 00:13:25.500 align:middle line:10%
Because the memory of
the girl who was killed

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:27.750 align:middle line:10%
was preserved in the
cells of her heart

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:33.390 align:middle line:10%
that are now in the body of
the new recipient, the younger

00:13:33.390 --> 00:13:37.680 align:middle line:10%
girl, and she was able
to share those memories

00:13:37.680 --> 00:13:39.060 align:middle line:10%
with the authorities.

00:13:39.060 --> 00:13:42.270 align:middle line:10%
And I'm sharing this story
with you for one reason.

00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:45.817 align:middle line:10%
That is how real the
memory is in our hearts.

00:13:45.817 --> 00:13:46.650 align:middle line:10%
It's not a metaphor.

00:13:46.650 --> 00:13:49.905 align:middle line:90%


00:13:49.905 --> 00:13:51.510 align:middle line:90%
>>SUE: This is remarkable.

00:13:51.510 --> 00:13:53.100 align:middle line:90%
How is this possible?

00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:56.520 align:middle line:84%
>>ROZMAN: Well, if you think
about what I said that there's

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:59.140 align:middle line:84%
sensory neurons in
the heart called

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:04.080 align:middle line:84%
a little brain in the heart
that neuro cardiologists have

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:08.730 align:middle line:84%
validated, then those
sensory neurons not

00:14:08.730 --> 00:14:13.680 align:middle line:84%
only sense and feel that
they learn and remember.

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:17.340 align:middle line:84%
So just like a memory in
your brain is imprinted,

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:22.470 align:middle line:84%
especially a strong memory like
what this child experienced,

00:14:22.470 --> 00:14:23.890 align:middle line:90%
the heart retains.

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:25.590 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
other books that

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:28.920 align:middle line:84%
talk about other case
studies of the same thing.

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:32.820 align:middle line:84%
It usually fades after a
while as the person's own soul

00:14:32.820 --> 00:14:35.310 align:middle line:90%
and spirit take over.

00:14:35.310 --> 00:14:38.520 align:middle line:84%
But it's been documented
numerous times

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:42.090 align:middle line:84%
that a transplant
recipient actually

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:45.990 align:middle line:84%
starts to want to eat
what the donor liked.

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:48.010 align:middle line:90%
And again, it's not a mystery.

00:14:48.010 --> 00:14:49.560 align:middle line:90%
There's neurons in the heart.

00:14:49.560 --> 00:14:51.210 align:middle line:84%
The fact that our
heart has a brain

00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:55.440 align:middle line:84%
and it functions independent
from this brain but they talk

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:57.900 align:middle line:90%
is a paradigm shift.

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:01.120 align:middle line:84%
That means we need to learn
how to interact with this heart

00:15:01.120 --> 00:15:04.063 align:middle line:84%
brain and what it's
designed to do.

00:15:04.063 --> 00:15:05.730 align:middle line:84%
>>SUE: We have known
of course, forever,

00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:08.460 align:middle line:84%
that the heart beats to keep
the body physically alive

00:15:08.460 --> 00:15:09.270 align:middle line:90%
et cetera.

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:12.090 align:middle line:84%
And now we're recognizing
that there are so many more

00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:13.710 align:middle line:90%
powers of the heart.

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:17.580 align:middle line:84%
Can you just kind of circle the
wagons here and land it for us?

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:19.890 align:middle line:84%
What else is it that
the heart is doing?

00:15:19.890 --> 00:15:24.300 align:middle line:84%
>>ROZMAN: Well, I'm not going
to say that I know everything

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:26.440 align:middle line:84%
because there's a lot of
mystery around the heart.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:30.000 align:middle line:84%
But what we do know and research
is the heart communicates

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.032 align:middle line:84%
with the brain and body
in at least four ways.

00:15:33.032 --> 00:15:34.740 align:middle line:84%
One way is what we've
been talking about,

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:37.920 align:middle line:84%
the neural traffic, the afferent
traffic the signals the heart

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:39.690 align:middle line:90%
sends to the brain.

00:15:39.690 --> 00:15:43.110 align:middle line:84%
And those signals are largely
transmitted through our heart

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:45.510 align:middle line:84%
rate variability, or
heart rhythm pattern,

00:15:45.510 --> 00:15:48.750 align:middle line:84%
and the brain pattern matches
from what's familiar to it.

00:15:48.750 --> 00:15:51.420 align:middle line:90%
And then it chooses a response.

00:15:51.420 --> 00:15:54.870 align:middle line:84%
We also know of course,
there's a blood pressure wave.

00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:58.110 align:middle line:84%
And that's not just
beating blood pressure

00:15:58.110 --> 00:15:59.190 align:middle line:90%
to keep us active.

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:01.650 align:middle line:84%
There's actually information
in the blood that

00:16:01.650 --> 00:16:04.410 align:middle line:84%
is informing the brain
and body in terms

00:16:04.410 --> 00:16:07.500 align:middle line:90%
of the wholeness of the system.

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:11.640 align:middle line:84%
Then there's the electromagnetic
field of the heart.

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:13.620 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
really exciting

00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:16.650 align:middle line:84%
because think of your heart
like a radio transmitter.

00:16:16.650 --> 00:16:21.450 align:middle line:84%
With every heartbeat, it's
putting out 2.5 watts of power.

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:25.230 align:middle line:84%
And just like a cell phone
tower or a radio transmitter,

00:16:25.230 --> 00:16:27.660 align:middle line:90%
it is radiating out that energy.

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:30.900 align:middle line:84%
And it can be measured three
to five feet from the body

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:32.130 align:middle line:90%
with magnetometers.

00:16:32.130 --> 00:16:34.905 align:middle line:84%
But most of us know
and feel that it

00:16:34.905 --> 00:16:37.200 align:middle line:90%
can go a lot farther than that.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:40.590 align:middle line:84%
And when that heart
beat is radiating,

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:42.840 align:middle line:84%
it is also sending
information just

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:46.900 align:middle line:84%
like a radio
station, a frequency.

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:49.760 align:middle line:84%
You tune the dial on
a radio to 101 FM,

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:52.200 align:middle line:84%
